    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I'm guessing you really don't need all columns for this, so don't use &quot;*&quot;. Also, that would likely disrupt the <code>COUNT</code> and <code>DISTINCT</code> for your needs.</p>\n<p>So instead of <code>ORDER BY</code>, use <code>GROUP BY</code> to get the info you need. You still need <code>ORDER BY</code> to get the list in order and add in <code>LIMIT</code> to get the largest amount of duplicates.</p>\n<pre><code>SELECT DISTINCT ID, COUNT(PROFILE) AS COUNT FROM USERDETAILS\nGROUP BY ID  \nORDER BY COUNT desc  \nLIMIT 1;\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 14535244,
      "reputation" : 164743,
      "user_id" : 10498828,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1193e109ef8ccd708ab3d234f32946af?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "forpas",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/10498828/forpas"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1639777483,
    "creation_date" : 1639777483,
    "answer_id" : 70399182,
    "question_id" : 70398305,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you don't care about ties in the number of duplicates then use a subquery in the <code>WHERE</code> clause:</p>\n<pre><code>SELECT * \nFROM Userdetails \nWHERE ID = (SELECT ID FROM Userdetails GROUP BY ID ORDER BY COUNT(*) DESC LIMIT 1);\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
